{
  "version": 2,
  "name": "Lissajous",
  "description": "Lissajous curve generator — a smooth morphing closed curve traced by the Lissajous parametric equations. The generator decomposes into an oscillator bank that smoothly modulates frequency, a frequency-selection mux that routes two of the three oscillators to the X and Y axes via a harmonic-ratio table, parallel curve builders on each axis that interpolate between integer-frequency Lissajous forms to eliminate scribbles, and finally a line renderer with optional vertex markers and animation.\n\nThe oscillator bank produces three continuously varying frequencies: two (lfo_x and lfo_y) oscillate smoothly from 0.5 to 3.5 and 1.0 to 5.0 Hz respectively to morph the curve shape, and a phase LFO ramps the phase accumulation parameter linearly from 0 to 2π. The clip_trigger card control routes the frequencies either through the smooth oscillators or through a curated 10-row harmonic-ratio table (ratio node) that jumps on retrigger.\n\nEach axis follows the same construction: the selected frequency is bracketed (floor and ceiling) by two math nodes, then subtracted to give the interpolation factor (a_lerp / b_lerp). A parameter array (t) ranges from 0 to 2π. Two parallel branches apply scale-and-offset to t using the floor and ceiling frequencies, then apply sine. The two sine outputs are blended by the interpolation factor to produce the final smooth mixed coordinate. This blending avoids closed-curve scribbles at non-integer frequencies by morphing smoothly between the clean integer cases.\n\nThe two axes are zipped into an Array<CurvePoint> by pack (which includes the legacy screen-fit scale factor), then render_lines carries the animation, vertex dots, and beat-flash rendering. The groups flatten to byte-identical behavior at load.",
